[4] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Tue 13 Feb 2018 3:03am
Source: ABC [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-02-13/whooping-cough-cases-spike-northern-queensland/9443528


Queensland's peak medical body is urging people to ensure their vaccinations are up to date after a spike in whooping cough cases in northern Queensland, including the recent diagnosis of a high school student. Parents were notified late last week [week of Sun 4 Feb 2018] after the Cairns student was suspected of suffering from whooping cough. That diagnosis has since been confirmed and is one of 37 cases in the north of the state this year [2018]. Only 10 cases had been reported by this time last year [2017].

Australian Medical Association Queensland Council of General Practice chairman Richard Kidd urged all Australians, particularly those in northern Queensland, to vaccinate against largely preventable diseases in the wake of the recent spike. "In pre-vaccination times [whooping cough] would kill at least one person in 10, and today sadly we will still see babies that will die because they haven't had the opportunity to get vaccinated," he said.

"For older children and adults who haven't been vaccinated, there's still a risk of dying from whooping cough."

Confirmed cases [annually] of whooping cough in northern Queensland, as [of] 13 Feb 2018: 2015 - 23; 2016 - 24; 2017 - 10; 2018 - 37.

[Byline: Anna Hartley, Sharon Molloy]

